{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504903"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2383"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2383"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.14,0.79,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107088"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"319"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"8869"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1575"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107088"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three hour history of severe pain in her right eye. She has an associated blurred vision in the right eye and a headache. She sees coloured bright circles when she looks at a light source.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in distress and discomfort. Her blood pressure is 134/90 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.2C. The eye examination shows conjunctival injection and corneal oedema. Visual acuity testing shows 6/6 in her left eye and she can only count fingers at 1 meter in her right eye. Her right eye remains dilated and fixed. Topical timolol is given in succession, one minute apart. Analgesia and antiemetics are provided for patient comfort.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"After topical eye drops, which of the following is the most appropriate next step in treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV ciprofloxacin","IV methylprednisolone","IV acetazolamide","IV cefotaxime","Subcutaneous sumatriptan"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely suffers from acute angle-closure glaucoma. The presence of an acute painful red eye with blurred vision and halos i.e. coloured bright circles when looking at a light source, oedematous cornea and conjunctiva injection is suggestive of acute angle-closure glaucoma. These symptoms are the result of increased intraocular pressure and distortion of the iris. There is commonly an associated fixed dilated pupil and frontal headache. Measurement of the intraocular pressure by tonometry gives the diagnosis of acute glaucoma which is then confirmed as angle closure by gonioscopy (usually performed by the on-call eye doctor/resident).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial pharmacotherapy includes topical eye drops such as timolol, apraclonidine and pilocarpine. These eye drops aim to reduce intraocular pressure temporarily while awaiting definitive treatment. Systemic treatments such as \u003Cstrong\u003EIV acetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E (a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor) inhibit carbonic anhydrase in the eye. This decreases the production of aqueous humour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic used to treat conjunctivitis. \u003Cstrong\u003ECefotaxime\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic used as empirical treatment of orbital cellulitis. \u003Cstrong\u003EMethylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a steroid used to decrease inflammation in severe ophthalmologic emergencies such as amaurosis fugax in temporal arteritis. \u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous sumatriptan\u003C/strong\u003E is used for cluster headaches.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alongside eye drops, IV acetazolamide is used in the initial emergency medical management of acute angle-closure glaucoma"],"references":["Congdon NG, Friedman DS. Angle-closure glaucoma: impact, etiology, diagnosis, and treatment. Curr Opin Ophthalmol 2003; 14:70.","Leibowitz HM. The red eye. N Engl J Med 2000; 343:345.","See JLS, Chew PTK. Angle-closure Glaucoma. In: Ophthalmology, 3rd, Yanoff M, Duker JS (Eds), Mosby, 2009. p.1162."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T06:53:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T06:53:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107088"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"